8897082¶

In this lab, we will work through a common practice of Deep Learning Engineers - that is - take an existing model, that does something similar to what the engineer is interested doing, and fine-tune it for the specific task at-hand.

This lab is the last one, so it is a bit more elaborated than the others. So make sure to take time to work through it.

A good starting point is to use the code in the notebook we went over in class - for fine-tuning VGG16.

The goal of this lab is to achieve the best classification performance over three classes (species) of birds. This should be done by exploring data augmentation and fine-tuning of a pre-trained model (VGG16). Finally, explore and describe the results.

If you are interested, you are encouraged to explore various training configurations, and see which one works better.

  1. Obtain the Data
    1. Download the BIRDS 525 SPECIES dataset from Kaggle (CC0 license). You will need to create a free Kaggle account, and this will provide you free access to many such datasets, as well as code and even online notebooks.
    2. Unpack the data. Notice that the data is organized into folders in a way similar to the Dogs vs Cats dataset that we worked with. This makes it easy to load with the same Keras function (ImageDataGenerator.flow_from_directory).
    3. For this lab, we will work with the 3 classes with the highest number of images. Identify those classes, and use only these for the next steps. You can delete/discard the others.
  2. Use data-augmentation to increase the number of training images. You are encouraged to try out various augmentation methods supported by Keras. The rule of thumb is that as long as an augmentation produces realistic images - it is probably a good idea to add it.(2 point)
  3. Fine-Tune VGG16 (pre-trained on imagenet), to classify the 3 classes (2 points)
  4. Explore the model performance: accuracy, confusion metric, precision, recall, F1-score, precision-recall curve and its area under the curve (AUC). Explore specific examples in which the model failed to predict correctly. (2 points)

import os
import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Flatten, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report
import pathlib

# Paths for train, validation, and test datasets
data_folder = pathlib.Path('../../data')
train_subdirs = os.listdir(data_folder / "train")
num_images_per_subdir = [(subdir, len(os.listdir(data_folder / "train" / subdir))) for subdir in train_subdirs]
sorted_subdirs = sorted(num_images_per_subdir, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
selected_subdirs = [subdir for subdir, _ in sorted_subdirs[:3]]

data_path = '../../data/'
train_path = os.path.join(data_path, 'train')
valid_path = os.path.join(data_path, 'valid')
test_path = os.path.join(data_path, 'test')

# Image augmentation settings for training data
train_img_gen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1.0/255.0,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    rotation_range=20,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    preprocessing_function=tf.keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input
)

# Image generator for validation and test without augmentation
valid_test_img_gen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1.0/255.0,
    preprocessing_function=tf.keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input
)

# Batching and loading training images
batch_size_train = 32
img_dim = (180, 180)
train_data_loader = train_img_gen.flow_from_directory(
    directory=train_path,
    target_size=img_dim,
    batch_size=batch_size_train,
    classes=selected_subdirs,
    class_mode='categorical'
)

# Batching and loading validation images
batch_size_valid = 32
valid_data_loader = valid_test_img_gen.flow_from_directory(
    directory=valid_path,
    target_size=img_dim,
    batch_size=batch_size_valid,
    classes=selected_subdirs,
    class_mode='categorical'
)
test_data_loader = valid_test_img_gen.flow_from_directory(
    directory=test_path,
    target_size=img_dim,
    batch_size=32,
    classes=selected_subdirs,
    class_mode='categorical'
)

# Load VGG16 without top layers
base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=img_dim + (3,))

# Set pre-trained VGG16 layers as non-trainable
for lyr in base_model.layers:
    lyr.trainable = False

# Designing our custom neural network
net_input = tf.keras.Input(shape=img_dim + (3,))
net = base_model(net_input, training=False)
net = Flatten()(net)
net = Dense(256)(net)
net = Dropout(0.5)(net)
net_output = Dense(train_data_loader.num_classes, activation="softmax")(net)
neural_net = tf.keras.Model(net_input, net_output)

# Compiling our neural network model
opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)
neural_net.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Training our model
training_epochs = 10
neural_net.fit(
    train_data_loader,
    epochs=training_epochs,
    validation_data=valid_data_loader
)

# Evaluating our model on test set
eval_loss, eval_accuracy = neural_net.evaluate(test_data_loader)
print("Evaluation Accuracy:", eval_accuracy)

# Performance on validation set
valid_eval_loss, valid_eval_accuracy = neural_net.evaluate(valid_data_loader)

# Predictions on test set
predictions = neural_net.predict(test_data_loader)
actual_labels = test_data_loader.classes

# Compute metrics
model_accuracy = np.mean(actual_labels == np.argmax(predictions, axis=1))
conf_mat = confusion_matrix(actual_labels, np.argmax(predictions, axis=1))
class_report = classification_report(actual_labels, np.argmax(predictions, axis=1), target_names=test_data_loader.class_indices.keys())

# Display metrics
print(f'Validation Set Accuracy: {valid_eval_accuracy:.2f}')
print(f'Test Set Accuracy: {model_accuracy:.2f}')
print('Confusion Matrix:')
print(conf_mat)
print('Classification Report:')
print(class_report)

# Compute precision-recall curve and its AUC for each category
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve, auc
prec = dict()
rec = dict()
area_under_curve = dict()
for idx in range(train_data_loader.num_classes):
    prec[idx], rec[idx], _ = precision_recall_curve(actual_labels == idx, predictions[:, idx])
    area_under_curve[idx] = auc(rec[idx], prec[idx])

# Visualization of precision-recall curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for idx in range(train_data_loader.num_classes):
    plt.plot(rec[idx], prec[idx], lw=2, label=f'Category {idx} (AUC = {area_under_curve[idx]:.2f})')

plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.title('Precision vs Recall Graph')
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()
